Thanks for the excellent style guide!

One thing that is not explicitly defined by the guide is inline comments. Can a section on this topic be added to the "Comments" section block, please?

For example,
```
let foo = 145; // This is modified below in the "baz()" function
```

Is this a legal line in the airbnb style?

And the follow-up question: if it is not legal, then I assume that the correct fix to have it be moved above, like this?

```
// This is modified below in the "baz()" function
let foo = 145;
```

Yet another follow-up question: if inline comments are legal, then what is the correct fix for in-line comments that make the line extend past 100 character? Like the following:

```
// This is a comment describing the following block of variable initializations
let foo = 123; // used in various contexts, but mostly for soccer games, basketball, and football games
let bar = 456; // used only for horse races; it is explicitly reset at the beginning of the "endRace()" function
let baz = 789; // used only for car races; it will be overwritten once we reach the "oilChange()" function
```

If it were moved above, it would overlap with the block comment header. So then does it make the most sense to move them down to the next line, like this?

```
// This is a comment describing the following block of variable initializations
let foo = 123;
// used in various contexts, but mostly for soccer games, basketball, and football games
let bar = 456;
// used only for horse races; it is explicitly reset at the beginning of the "endRace()" function
let baz = 789;
// used only for car races; it will be overwritten once we reach the "oilChange()" function
```

Hi,
The example of [18.1 Use /** ... */ for multi-line comments](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#comments--multiline) is confusing my team as they though they should **not use @param** or other JSDoc features.

Does it make more sense to be more consistent in good and bad like in the below example:

```javascript
// bad
// make() returns a new element
// based on the passed in tag name
//
// @param {String} tag
// @return {Element} element
function make(tag) {

  // ...

  return element;
}

// good
/**
 * make() returns a new element
 * based on the passed-in tag name
 *
 * @param {String} tag
 * @return {Element} element
 */
function make(tag) {

  // ...

  return element;
}
```

Prefer namespace imports when importing more than **n** exports from a module.

```js
// bad
import {map, reduce, filter} from 'lodash';

// good 
import * as _ from 'lodash';
```

### Why?
Mainly git diff results. With namespace imports we don't have to touch the importing line. 

It's also making the namespace variable more discoverable using the code-completion tools. Hitting `_.` will prompt all exports of lodash in editors that support interlisense

@ljharb sorry for hijacking https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/issues/1447 after you mentioned discouraging colocation of tests with source files, but i am legitimately curious about your reasons.

you mentioned the more obvious piece about tool compatibility, which i think eslint is the last of in my case, though i won't be surprised if i realize that i forgot about something once i try. with the breadth of tools you maintain, i'm sure you have reasons that would be worth considering if i take steps closer to colocation. 

my main motivations to move to colocation are mostly around code that changes together being packaged together. working with react has even further strengthened this thought process for me since packaging all parts of a component together provides so many benefits. in addition, dropping the need to navigate up and back down a deeply nested directory structure for every source import from a test. would certainly be nice as well.
